{"id":"spgr-jpp.37","title":"LeaseDuration and ExtendBy proto fields have no minimum/maximum enforcement","description":"ClaimSpecRequest.LeaseDuration and HeartbeatRequest.ExtendBy (proto/specgraph/v1/claim.proto and gen/specgraph/v1/claim.pb.go) accept any google.protobuf.Duration value including zero, negative, or arbitrarily large values. The only invariant is a comment '(default 15m)'.

In internal/server/claim_handler.go line ~4647:
  claim, err := h.store.ClaimSpec(ctx, msg.Slug, msg.Agent, msg.LeaseDuration.AsDuration())

If LeaseDuration is nil (omitted from request), this panics with a nil pointer dereference on msg.LeaseDuration.AsDuration() because AsDuration() is called on a nil *durationpb.Duration pointer. The memgraph implementation handles zero-duration by defaulting to 15m, but the handler itself does not guard against nil.

Suggested fix for the nil panic: Guard with:
  var leaseDuration time.Duration
  if msg.LeaseDuration != nil {
      leaseDuration = msg.LeaseDuration.AsDuration()
  }

Additionally, consider validating that the duration is positive and within a reasonable bound (e.g., max 24h) at the handler layer to enforce the invariant that lease durations are meaningful.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-01T00:38:44Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-01T00:38:44Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/4"}

{"id":"spgr-jpp.57","title":"UpdateSpec and UpdateDecision share identical partial-update pattern — candidate for extraction","description":"Both internal/storage/memgraph/memgraph.go UpdateSpec and internal/storage/memgraph/decision.go UpdateDecision use the identical pattern for building dynamic Cypher SET clauses from optional pointer fields: declare a setClauses slice and params map, range over the optional fields appending to both, guard on empty result, then append the updated_at clause and run fmt.Sprintf to build the query.

