{"id":"spgr-jpp.34","title":"Duplicated client-factory boilerplate across all five CLI files","description":"Every CLI file (claim.go, decision.go, edge.go, health.go, spec.go) contains an identically-structured two-line client-factory function that calls resolveBaseURL() then the service-specific New*Client constructor. The refactor commit extracted resolveBaseURL and newHTTPClient into client.go, but left the per-service wrapper duplicated across five files.

Repeated pattern:
func xyzClient() (specgraphv1connect.XyzServiceClient, error) {
    baseURL, err := resolveBaseURL()
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }
    return specgraphv1connect.NewXyzServiceClient(newHTTPClient(), baseURL), nil
}

Files: cmd/specgraph/claim.go:24-30, decision.go:158-164, edge.go:319-325, health.go:658-664, spec.go:947-958.

These could be replaced by a generic helper in client.go:
func newClient[C any](ctor func(*http.Client, string, ...connect.ClientOption) C) (C, error) {
    baseURL, err := resolveBaseURL()
    if err != nil {
        var zero C
        return zero, err
    }
    return ctor(newHTTPClient(), baseURL), nil
}

Or, more simply, inline the two-line body at each call site and delete the five factory functions, since the factories add no abstraction value over the inline form. The generic approach is cleaner but requires Go 1.21+; verify module requirements before choosing.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-01T00:38:39Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-01T00:38:39Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/4"}

{"id":"spgr-gk1.112","title":"marshalJSON comment inaccurate for typed nil interface values","description":"File: internal/storage/memgraph/constitution.go, line 7524

The comment reads:
  // marshalJSON marshals v to a JSON string. Returns "{}" for nil values.

This is inaccurate. The nil check `v == nil` only fires for an untyped nil interface value. When a typed nil pointer is passed (e.g., constitution.Tech is (*specv1.TechConfig)(nil)), the interface value is non-nil (it has a type descriptor), so the nil branch is skipped and json.Marshal is called on the typed nil pointer, returning "null" — not "{}" .

This matters because unmarshalIfPresent skips "null" (listed as a sentinel), but callers that expect "{}" for nil pointer fields will instead get "null". The comment misleads callers into expecting "{}" uniformly.

Suggested fix: Either (a) update the comment to accurately describe the behavior:
  // marshalJSON marshals v to a JSON string. Returns "{}" for untyped nil.
  // Typed nil pointers marshal to "null" via json.Marshal.
Or (b) use reflect to detect typed nils and return "{}" consistently, and update the comment to match.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-01T18:25:00Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-01T18:25:00Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/7"}

{"id":"spgr-gk1.99","title":"Proto Principle field named 'statement' diverges from plan spec which specifies 'principle'","description":"The Slice 2 implementation plan (docs/plans/2026-02-28-slice-2-constitution-plan.md) specifies the Principle proto message as:

    message Principle {
      string id = 1;
      string principle = 2;   // <-- field name in plan
      string rationale = 3;
      string exceptions = 4;
    }

The actual implementation in proto/specgraph/v1/constitution.proto uses:

    message Principle {
      string id = 1;
      string statement = 2;   // <-- renamed from 'principle'
      string rationale = 3;
      string exceptions = 4;
    }

This is an intentional divergence (the name 'statement' is more descriptive and consistent with the YAML struct ConstitutionPrinciple.Statement). The change propagates correctly through all layers (emitter, CLI show, YAML bootstrap). However it is undocumented — the plan still shows the old field name. The plan doc should be updated to reflect the actual proto schema. Similarly the Reference message changed from {string type, string path} to {ReferenceType reference_type, string path} — an improvement not reflected in the plan doc.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-01T18:22:37Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-01T18:22:37Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/7"}

{"id":"spgr-0oj.30","title":"TransitionStage takes stage names as raw strings, bypassing ValidateTransition type safety","description":"internal/storage/authoring.go:146 — TransitionStage(ctx, slug, from, to string) accepts stage names as untyped strings. The from/to arguments at every call site in authoring_handler.go are the stage string constants (authoring.StageSpark, authoring.StageShape, etc.), but the interface signature itself enforces nothing.

A caller passing ('spark', 'approved') — skipping multiple stages — gets a runtime ErrInvalidStageTransition rather than a compile error. More critically, the from argument is not validated by the storage layer at all in some implementations (the memgraph implementation was not reviewed here but the interface contract does not require from-validation).

Suggested fix: Define a Stage type (type Stage string) in the storage package, use it in TransitionStage and AmendSpec signatures, and expose the stage constants as Stage values. The handler's stageToProto / protoToStage maps already do the string-to-typed-value translation, so this would be a clean change.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-03T01:09:12Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-03T01:36:21Z","closed_at":"2026-03-03T01:36:21Z","close_reason":"Out of scope: TransitionStage string params follow the existing Backend interface pattern from Slice 1. Refactoring to typed stages is a cross-cutting change.","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-a4b.25","title":"SafetyResultsToProto silently maps unknown FindingSeverity to UNSPECIFIED proto value","description":"In internal/authoring/safety.go, SafetyResultsToProto uses a map lookup with no fallback check:

```go
var severityToProto = map[FindingSeverity]specv1.FindingSeverity{
    SeverityCritical: specv1.FindingSeverity_FINDING_SEVERITY_CRITICAL,
    SeverityWarning:  specv1.FindingSeverity_FINDING_SEVERITY_WARNING,
    SeverityNote:     specv1.FindingSeverity_FINDING_SEVERITY_NOTE,
}

func SafetyResultsToProto(flags []SafetyFlagResult) []*specv1.SafetyFlag {
    out[i] = &specv1.SafetyFlag{
        Severity: severityToProto[f.Severity],  // zero value = UNSPECIFIED if key missing
```

If a new FindingSeverity constant is added to safety.go without updating severityToProto, the resulting proto will have FINDING_SEVERITY_UNSPECIFIED (0) instead of a meaningful severity. This failure is completely silent — no log, no error, no panic. The caller sees a safety flag with severity UNSPECIFIED and no indication of a mapping problem.

Fix: add an explicit default or panic/error on unmapped severity:
```go
protoSev, ok := severityToProto[f.Severity]
if !ok {
    protoSev = specv1.FindingSeverity_FINDING_SEVERITY_NOTE // or log a warning
}
```","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-03T04:23:02Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-03T04:23:02Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-a4b.18","title":"CLI --json-file flag accepts arbitrary filesystem paths without restriction","description":"Files: cmd/specgraph/util.go, cmd/specgraph/shape.go, cmd/specgraph/specify.go, cmd/specgraph/decompose.go

`loadJSONFile` reads an arbitrary path provided by the user via the `--json-file` CLI flag and unmarshals it as a proto message:

    func loadJSONFile[T proto.Message](path string, msg T) error {
        data, err := os.ReadFile(path)
        ...
        if err := protojson.Unmarshal(data, msg); err != nil {
        ...

There is no path restriction (e.g. no check that the path is within a permitted directory, no rejection of absolute paths or path traversal sequences). In a CLI tool where the user supplies the path directly, this is generally acceptable. However, if this utility function is later reused in a context where the path comes from a network request or config file, it becomes a path traversal risk.

Additionally, `protojson.Unmarshal` is used with default options, which by default discards unknown fields rather than rejecting them. This is not a security bug but means extra fields in the JSON file are silently ignored rather than flagged.

Suggestion: Add a comment that `path` must be user-supplied only (CLI context) and should not be used in server-side code paths. For the proto unmarshal, consider using `protojson.UnmarshalOptions{DiscardUnknown: false}` to surface unexpected input.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-03T04:22:44Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-03T04:22:44Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-a4b.44","title":"config.go TLS field addition changes URL scheme behavior without migration documentation","description":"File: internal/config/config.go, line ~2298; cmd/specgraph/client.go, line ~106.

A new TLS bool field is added to ServerConfig:

  TLS bool `yaml:\"tls\"`

The default is false (Go zero value), so existing config files without this field continue to use HTTP, which is backward-compatible for local dev. However, the URL scheme selection in client.go now gates on this field:

  scheme := \"http\"
  if cfg.Server.TLS {
      scheme = \"https\"
  }

Before this PR, the URL was always constructed as http://. Any user who has an existing config with Server.Remote pointing to an HTTPS endpoint and no TLS: true in their config will silently continue using HTTP (Remote is used as-is when set, bypassing scheme selection). The subtle issue is that the new TLS field only affects the auto-constructed URL from Host+Port, not the Remote field — this inconsistency is undocumented.

Suggested fix: Add a code comment or config documentation noting that TLS only affects auto-URL construction (Host+Port mode) and has no effect when Remote is set.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-03T04:23:59Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-03T04:23:59Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-s34.17","title":"Shape/Specify/Decompose RPCs hardcode 'from' stage, coupling authoring funnel strictly to sequential ordering","description":"Each of the Shape, Specify, and Decompose handlers hardcodes both the 'from' and 'to' stage parameters in their TransitionStage calls:

  // Shape handler - internal/server/authoring_handler.go line ~2612
  h.store.TransitionStage(ctx, msg.Slug, storage.AuthoringStage(authoring.StageSpark), storage.AuthoringStage(authoring.StageShape))

  // Specify handler - line ~2658
  h.store.TransitionStage(ctx, msg.Slug, storage.AuthoringStage(authoring.StageShape), storage.AuthoringStage(authoring.StageSpecify))

  // Decompose handler - line ~2705
  h.store.TransitionStage(ctx, msg.Slug, storage.AuthoringStage(authoring.StageSpecify), storage.AuthoringStage(authoring.StageDecompose))

This means: if a spec was amended back to Spark stage and the user calls Specify (skipping Shape), the call will fail with CodeFailedPrecondition because the server checks the actual DB stage against the hardcoded 'from'. This is the correct rejection behavior, but the error message does not tell the client what stage the spec is currently at or what stage is required.

From an API contract perspective, the RPCs for Shape/Specify/Decompose do not document the required entry-stage precondition, leaving clients guessing what CodeFailedPrecondition means. The proto comments should state 'requires spec to be at stage X' for each RPC.

Suggested fix: Add a proto comment to each RPC (or its Request message) documenting the required entry stage. Optionally return a richer error detail (connect.ErrorDetail) with the current stage and the expected stage.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-04T01:23:40Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-04T01:23:40Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-s34.57","title":"SupersedeSpec storage error wrapping loses ErrSpecNotFound identity for the superseded_by spec","description":"In internal/storage/memgraph/authoring.go, the SupersedeSpec implementation checks both specs exist:

  if _, err := s.GetSpec(ctx, slug); err != nil {
      return fmt.Errorf("memgraph: supersede spec: old spec %q: %w", slug, err)
  }
  if _, err := s.GetSpec(ctx, supersededBy); err != nil {
      return fmt.Errorf("memgraph: supersede spec: new spec %q: %w", supersededBy, err)
  }

Both calls correctly wrap ErrSpecNotFound using %w, so errors.Is(err, storage.ErrSpecNotFound) will return true for both.

However, the handler in authoring_handler.go only checks ErrSpecNotFound:
  if errors.Is(err, storage.ErrSpecNotFound) {
      return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeNotFound, err)
  }

This is correct behavior. But when the superseded_by spec is not found, the client receives CodeNotFound with a message like 'memgraph: supersede spec: new spec "nonexistent": ...'. This error message includes internal implementation details ('memgraph: supersede spec: new spec').

The proto contract does not document which slug is not found in CodeNotFound responses, but clients cannot distinguish 'slug not found' from 'superseded_by not found' without parsing internal error text.

Suggested fix: Use connect.ErrorDetail to include a structured payload (e.g. a proto message with a 'missing_slug' field), or return different error messages that clients can pattern-match without depending on internal implementation details.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-04T01:25:06Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-04T01:25:06Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-s34.58","title":"[comments] TransitionStage godoc says ErrSpecAlreadyApproved when from is approved stage but doesn't document the approved-block behavior at storage layer","description":"File: internal/storage/memgraph/authoring.go, TransitionStage method.

The godoc reads:
  // TransitionStage validates and applies a spec's stage transition.
  // It first checks the transition is valid via authoring.ValidateTransition,
  // then updates the spec's stage in the database. Returns ErrSpecNotFound if
  // the spec doesn't exist, or ErrInvalidStageTransition if the spec is at
  // a different stage than expected. Returns ErrSpecAlreadyApproved if from
  // is the approved stage.

The comment is correct but the order of operations described is slightly wrong: the code actually checks for the approved-stage guard BEFORE calling ValidateTransition:
  if from == authoring.StageApproved {
      return storage.ErrSpecAlreadyApproved
  }
  if err := authoring.ValidateTransition(...); err != nil { ... }

This is a minor inaccuracy — the comment implies ValidateTransition is checked first ('It first checks the transition is valid via authoring.ValidateTransition'), but the approved-stage guard takes priority. Low impact but could mislead someone debugging why a APPROVED->anything call returns ErrSpecAlreadyApproved rather than ErrInvalidStageTransition.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-04T01:25:07Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-04T01:25:07Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-s34.44","title":"[comments] DecomposeResponse proto fields simplicity and constitution_violations appear unimplemented but have no caveat in docs","description":"File: proto/specgraph/v1/authoring.proto, DecomposeResponse message.

The proto documents DecomposeResponse.simplicity and DecomposeResponse.constitution_violations as regular fields with positive descriptions. However, the server handler (authoring_handler.go) has a TODO showing these fields are NOT yet populated:

  // TODO(authoring): Wire simplicity_check and constitution_check analytical
  // passes to populate the Decompose response.

The proto comments give no indication that these fields are always empty in the current server implementation. A client developer relying on the proto docs alone would assume these fields are populated.

Similarly, SparkResponse.constitution_violations, ShapeResponse.constitution_violations, SpecifyResponse.constitution_violations are all undocumented as unimplemented — the handler code does not populate constitution_violations for any stage.

Recommendation: add a note like '// NOTE: not yet populated by the server — see TODO in authoring_handler.go' or mark as reserved, until wiring is complete. This prevents client developers from writing code that silently never receives expected data.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-04T01:24:33Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-04T01:24:33Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-s34.41","title":"[simplify] memgraph/authoring.go: StoreDecomposeOutput redundant nil-check after ErrSpecNotFound branch","description":"File: internal/storage/memgraph/authoring.go (lines ~3826-3840)

In StoreDecomposeOutput, after GetSpec returns ErrSpecNotFound, execution falls into the inner if-block and calls CreateSpec. Then there is a dead else-if branch:

    existing, getErr := s.GetSpec(ctx, childSlug)
    if getErr != nil {
        if !errors.Is(getErr, storage.ErrSpecNotFound) {
            return nil, ...  // non-404 error
        }
        // Not found — proceed to create.
        if _, err := s.CreateSpec(...); err != nil { ... }
    } else if existing == nil {  // <-- dead branch: GetSpec never returns (nil, nil)
        if _, err := s.CreateSpec(...); err != nil { ... }
    }

GetSpec returns either (spec, nil) or (nil, err) — it never returns (nil, nil). The else-if branch creates identical code to the ErrSpecNotFound block but can never be reached.

Suggested fix: Remove the else-if branch entirely, or collapse both CreateSpec calls into one:

    if errors.Is(getErr, storage.ErrSpecNotFound) {
        if _, err := s.CreateSpec(ctx, childSlug, ...); err != nil {
            return nil, fmt.Errorf("memgraph: create child spec %q: %w", childSlug, err)
        }
    } else if getErr != nil {
        return nil, fmt.Errorf("memgraph: check child spec %q: %w", childSlug, getErr)
    }
    // else: spec already exists, continue","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-04T01:24:32Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-04T01:24:32Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-s34.3","title":"[security] Internal error messages include slug values and storage details in CodeInternal responses","description":"File: internal/server/authoring_handler.go, lines 2589, 2627, 2673, 2720 (and others)

Several CodeInternal error responses include the spec slug and internal storage context in the error message returned to the caller:

    return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeInternal, fmt.Errorf("store spark output for spec %q: %w", msg.Slug, err))
    return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeInternal, fmt.Errorf("store shape output for spec %q: %w", msg.Slug, err))
    return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeInternal, fmt.Errorf("store specify output for spec %q: %w", msg.Slug, err))
    return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeInternal, fmt.Errorf("store decompose output for spec %q: %w", msg.Slug, err))

The slug itself is low-sensitivity (it came from the caller), but the wrapped storage error (err) may contain Cypher query fragments, Memgraph driver error details, or internal identifiers. These are propagated verbatim to the client via ConnectRPC error metadata.

Similarly in storeJSONProperty (memgraph/authoring.go line 3987):
    return fmt.Errorf("memgraph: marshal %s: %w", property, err)

The property name and marshal error detail are included in errors that bubble up to CodeInternal responses.

Recommended fix: Log the full internal error server-side (with structured logging), and return only a generic message to the client for CodeInternal errors. For example: 'internal error storing spark output' without wrapping the raw storage error.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-04T01:22:54Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-04T01:22:54Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

{"id":"spgr-s34.8","title":"[security] Scanner walks arbitrary caller-supplied filesystem path with no containment","description":"Files: internal/scanner/walk.go, internal/scanner/tier1.go, internal/scanner/tier2.go

The ScanTier1 and ScanTier2 functions accept a root path that is used directly with filepath.WalkDir without any containment or sanitization:

    // walk.go line 2469
    err := filepath.WalkDir(root, func(path string, d fs.DirEntry, err error) error {

    // tier2.go line 2257
    absDir := filepath.Join(root, dir)
    skipped, err := walkGoFiles(absDir, false, fset, ...)

In ScanTier2, each element of the dirs slice is joined with root — if a caller passes a dirs entry like '../../../etc', the resulting absDir escapes the intended root. The test in edge_test.go covers symlinks and malformed files but does not test directory escape via the dirs parameter.

Current risk is limited because:
- ScanTier1/ScanTier2 are not directly exposed via RPC in this PR
- The scanner is called from CLI context where the user controls the path

However, if scanner functions are later called from an RPC or webhook handler (a reasonable Phase 2 extension), an unvalidated path becomes a server-side directory traversal vulnerability allowing an attacker to read any readable Go file on the server.

Recommended fix: Add a check that absDir in ScanTier2 resolves to a path under root after calling filepath.EvalSymlinks. This is defense-in-depth that prevents future callers from accidentally introducing traversal.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"4678+seanb4t@users.noreply.github.com","created_at":"2026-03-04T01:23:22Z","created_by":"seanb4t","updated_at":"2026-03-04T01:23:22Z","external_ref":"https://github.com/seanb4t/specgraph/pull/8"}

